339.title: Starblazer ; no. 4 The Edge of Infinity.
339.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "With the Galactic Union of Earth desperately short of fuel, survey vessels were sent out to locate new sources. That was when the Barrier was discovered, an impenetrable forcefield millions of miles from Earth on the Galactic Rim. No one knew why it was there, or who had put it there. 340.title: Starblazer ; no. 5 The Shipeater.
340.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "By the year 3000, vast areas of the galaxy had been opened up for trading. Mineral-rich planets attracted Starfreighters of all sizes. The Space Patrol scouted up and down the starlanes, constantly on the alert for trouble of any kind. And it was trouble of an unknown kind that struck Space Patrol Vessel Utopia."

341.title: Starblazer ; no. 7 Holocaust Hogan.
341.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "A.D. 2500. As Man reached out to explore distant worlds, he also took some of his problems along with him. The Space Federation was formed to keep law and order in the galaxy. With such a large area to patrol, pirate mineral prospecting was rife. Alpha-1, a Space Federation patrol ship, sped unerringly on the trail of one such pirate prospector. Captain Holocaust Hogan was at the helm."

342.title: Starblazer ; no. 8 Planet of Fear.
342.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "The deep space miners were a tough and hardened breed of men who blazed the way across the unknown wilderness of space. Theirs was a dangerous business, where the risks and the rewards were high. Sarana looked a promising planet. It was completely dry and barren, every single drop of water had to be space-lifted across a thousand light years. But at least it was harmless. Or so they thought as they set up camp and began mining."

343.title: Starblazer ; no. 9 Lancer the Lawlord.
343.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Time-warp opened up galaxies many light years distant. To patrol them, the Galactic Federation formed a corps of specially trained men to do for space what the fearless marshals did for the early West. They called them the Lawlords. Their oath, to bring justice to the wild desolation of space, to be judge, jury and sometimes executioner."

344.title: Starblazer ; no. 10 Terror Satellite.
344.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Long, long before the first dinosaur roared on Earth, sometime, somewhere in a forgotten layer of eternity the Yakutzees began their wanderings. Flipping back and forth across the Universe through space and time in their galactic ark, they had seen the blinding splendour of flaring super novae, and fought against the gravity of collapsed white dwarf stars. A thousand centuries later they decided to end their voyaging and so sought a permanent home. And the planet they chose was known to its inhabitants as Earth."

345.title: Starblazer ; no. 11 The Purple Planet.
345.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Out deep in the far reaches of infinity, many strange life forms exist. Some insular, some peaceful, some aggressive, some inquisitive, and some you can't comprehend. This is the story of three life forms, one human, one aggressive and one from the Purple Planet."

346.title: Starblazer ; no. 12 The Web of Arcon.
346.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Reconnaissance ships patrolled the dark recesses of the galaxy. As these ships were largely automatic the crew spent long periods doing nothing. Boredom set in, and some people took terrible risks to relieve the boredom. On his first deep space trip was the newly commissioned Lieutenant Janus."

347.title: Starblazer ; no. 14 Battlecruiser Revenge.
347.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Over the years the Earth had colonised many planets. One of the largest colonies claimed independence, but the Terran Council refused. The colonists resorted to violence. A powerful Terran force crushed the rebellion, and the colonists were expelled to a distant planet, Pi Centurai. Over hundreds of years the Centurai became almost as strong as the Earth Union. Now they returned, seeking revenge."

348.title: Starblazer ; no. 15 Algol the Terrible.
348.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "The Galaxy was governed by the peaceful alliance of the Hub. But out across 50,000 light years, the wild Galactic Frontier had fallen under the tyranny of the Starbarons. From their homeworld, Abraxis, the evil warlords sent mighty battlecruisers to crush all thoughts of rebellion. Their aim was total domination of the galaxy, and Algol the Terrible was in command of the stormtroops."

349.title: Starblazer ; no. 16 The Secret of Soma.
349.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "The Galaxy was a collection of independent worlds living and trading peacefully. Earth held a prominent place because of its supplies of ficamite, the mineral that made faster than light travel a reality. Most worlds traded and bartered for ficamite, but the Soma demanded more than their share, and threatened to wipe out the population of Earth unless their demands were met."

350.title: Starblazer ; no. 17 The Caverns of Korad.
350.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Throughout the Galaxy spin many dead planets. Some have never had life, some life was destroyed by war or weather. Some have forms of life unrecognized by others, and some have secret, concealed life. Such was the case with The Caverns of Korad."

351.title: Starblazer ; no. 18 Abandon Earth.
351.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Space wars did not exist. By a series of treaties each galaxy remained alone and untouched. Earth built a survey ship, Zephyrus, to prospect in deep space. It was this ship that led to the call, 'Abandon Earth'."

352.title: Starblazer ; no. 19 Sinister City.
352.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Earth had endured fifteen years of oppression by the occupying overlords of the all-conquering Emperor of the Planet Sinister. Gradually the forces of freedom recovered and reformed in the aftermath of the humiliating invasion. A whole new generation of Earthmen were ready to try to win freedom, but first they had to reach the Sinister City."

353.title: Starblazer ; no. 20 The Doomsday Machines.
353.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Stentor III seemed a paradise planet for colonists: fertile, temperate, uninhabited. Many colonists left an overcrowded Earth to begin a new life far from the ceaseless noise of machinery. But they didn't know that they were about to face the Doomsday Machines."

354.title: Starblazer ; no. 21 Robot Rebellion.
354.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "The Earth Federation fought to keep the war-mongering Varloks at bay. The war that ranged across the Galaxy was violent and bitter. Both sides were exhausted with no reserves to fall back on. Very little was needed to tip the balance and bring total victory to the side that could gain the first advantage. And the Varloks had just developed that advantage."

355.title: Starblazer ; no. 23 Slaveship of Simala.
355.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "By the year 2180, energy sources were at a premium. Some galaxies had all but drained their sources of energy. Exploratory craft were sent out. Such a craft was the giant Simala Queen, out on the Galactic rim. It arrived in the area of Petrula, a planet which orbited a large star. This star was a solid diamond which reflected and channelled light to the surface of Petrula. Petrula also had a source of energy, people. People destined for the Slaveship of Simala."

356.title: Starblazer ; no. 24 Avenging Angel.
356.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Joe 'Acer' Angel earned his nickname during the Galactic War. Acer flew his AK-40 Angel Fighter non-stop from Earth in an attempt to halt the advance of the hated Arkan warmongers. Although the Galactic Federation controlled all the supplies of the power crystal Trypzium, somehow the Arkans were buying it to fuel their war-machines. And if the sellers couldn't be found, it could mean the end of the Federation."

357.title: Starblazer ; no. 25 Galactic Shootout.
357.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Space was a vast haven for the dregs of every world. Smugglers, hi-jackers and pirates roamed the depths plundering cargo vessels. The law enforcement agencies fought a constant battle to clear space of these parasitic criminals, and often it was a losing battle. Rik Tor, a young law enforcement officer, had the task of tracking criminals all over known space, and his task always ended in a Galactic Shootout."

358.title: Starblazer ; no. 26 Alien Contact.
358.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Even before man took the first steps into space searching for new planets, stars and galaxies, he often felt that he was being watched, but what happens when man meets his watchers? These thoughts were not very far from Matt Crane's mind as he searched unknown space for a missing explorer craft, one of many to disappear."

359.title: Starblazer ; no. 27 The Drifters of Darga.
359.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Transmitting matter by energy beam replaced starfreighters in the year 2281. Across the vast reaches of space, energy beams relayed vast tonnages of freight from station to station. Whoever controlled the beams, controlled the Universe, and it was at the planet Darga two Earthmen tried desperately to keep control from falling into the hands of the evil Porgan killers."

360.title: Starblazer ; no. 78 Doorway to Death.
360.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "Earth was the only civilised planet in the Four Quadrants region, and it was safe from attack, as even faster than light craft would take centuries to reach it from the nearest alien power. But restless souls still did exist, like Rik Moran, a pilot with a burning ambition, and ultimately a terrible responsibility."

361.title: Starblazer ; no. 175 The Black Lord.
361.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "It was a time long after Earth's seventh ice age. Dynasties had fallen, but civilisation of a sort was returning, and some of the ancient technology had been restored. But there were those who were able to use a far greater power, the dark arts, magic, sorcery, and one was the Black Lord."

362.title: Starblazer ; no. 238 The Prince and the Peasant.
362.author: [No author]
notes: Begins: "On a distant planet where time had still not been defined lived a race of men. Legend had it that their ancestors were gods, who had come from the skies in chariots of fire. But these men had descended to the primitive. One such was Marak, and it was to him a warning came as he herded stock, mounted on the great Rork he had captured and gentled."
